sh Revolution. The work of John Walter has played a central role in defining current understanding of the field and has been widely read and cited by those working on the politics of subaltern groups. This collection of essays offers a radical re-evaluation of the nature of crowds and protests during the period, and it will make fascinating reading for historians of the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aCivil War.  aEnglish Revolution.  aMaldon.  aOxfordshire rising.  aauthority.  acollective protest.  aearly modern England.  agrain riots.  amarket integration.  apopular attitudes.  apopular political agency.  apopular political culture.  apopular politics.  apopular protest.  apopulation explosion.  aproto-royalists.  apublic transcripts.  aregional specialisation.  aurbanisation.1 aWalter, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779397340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847793973423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847793973/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles